thread.title: Washington volleyball sweeps Oregon State
thread.title_full: Washington volleyball sweeps Oregon State | The Seattle Times

author: Seattle Times staff
title: Washington volleyball sweeps Oregon State
text:
A balanced attack led by the 12 kills from sophomore Tia Scambray powered the fourth-ranked Washington volleyball team to a sweep of Oregon State at Alaska Airlines Arena on Wednesday.
Six Husky attackers had five or more kills, as Washington (16-1, 6-1 Pac-12) finished with 20 more kills than the Beavers (4-13, 2-5 Pac-12) and closed strong in all three sets for the 25-13, 25-22, 25-20 victory.
With the win, the Huskies tied a program record with 24 consecutive Pac-12 home victories dating to the first win of 2013. The run equals a mark set over the 2004-07 seasons.
Cassie Strickland had 15 digs. Lianna Sybeldon had seven kills on a .500 attack percentage and added five block assists.

In the coaches poll, Seattle U collected 22 points. New Mexico State received all seven possible first-place votes followed by Grand Canyon with 39 points. New Mexico State was also selected as the preseason favorite in the media poll, picking up 13 of 14 first-place votes and 110 points overall. Grand Canyon earned 88 points to finish just ahead of Missouri-Kansas City with 87 points. Seattle U collected 55 points for fifth place.
Junior William Powell was chosen to the second team by both the coaches and the media. He is the leading returner for the Redhawks in both scoring and rebounding after averaging 7.8 points and 6.4 rebounds per game. Deshaun Sunderhaus also was a second-team pick by the media.
• The Seattle U women’s basketball team was picked to finish third by the coaches and fourth by the media. 
In the coaches poll, the Redhawks received 33 points and one first place vote and in the media poll, received 48 points.
Reigning WAC tournament champion New Mexico State was picked to finish first, receiving a majority of the first-place votes in both polls. 
In the coaches poll, Taelor Ross represented SU on the preseason first team while Crystal Allen was named to the second team. In the media poll, Ross was named to the second team.
From sports-information reports.
